snippet.textDisplay: Thanks for doing the testing of these current Dual Cab 4x4's. It has only reinforced that I'm still far better off in my 130. Bigger brakes than the Amarok with Disks all round and 4 piston calliper factory fitted that can be even further upgraded if so desired. Bigger rear tub than all except the width of the Amarok (I believe their about the same-ish in Volume). Full time 4 wheel drive with the easiest win for the lowest low range Transfer box, plus I have a center diff lock as well. I don't have front or rear diff locks but those can be easily fitted using a far superior Ashcroft or TJM Pro Locker than the factory offerings on these Dual Cabs. I could keep going but I don't have all night, as I said, just glad you reinforced my choice, so Thanks

snippet.textDisplay: Great VID. These are pick ups. The name Ute was used to describe a utility vehicle developed in Australia in the 1930s and the name died with the collapse of the Australian passenger car industry in the early part of 21 century. The dual cab pick-up was then imported to partly fill the gap left by the demise of the real Australian Ute.

If only the wife liked the shape and interior of the Triton, which she regretted and kicks herself over, we would have gone the Triton. Plus one for the AWD system and only brain dead dickheads kick the tail out on public roads.

snippet.textDisplay: Comprehensive test, Yes. Honest & Unbiased, I don't think so. With the Amarok (bashing) you mentioned lack of engine braking, but this vehicle has an excellent hill-descent-control system, why no mention when you praised the modern traction-control systems. You highlighted the front air intake, but some other models are the same. You mentioned the lack of no low range, but other 'industry experts' claim the 8 speed box is that lowly geared that it makes up for it. PLUS other model short comings, whilst raised, didn't receive the same bagging as others. Great test, but consistency when rating is a must & I don't believe you got there. Sorry.

snippet.textDisplay: I used to work in the 4wd industry, designing aftermarket accessories, and that included testing, lots of fun testing!! I like that you inspected the chassis of all the units and can finally say they are all 'similar', and you mentioned that they are designed to flex, bonus points!! I don't like the little motors in some of the units, would love to see an actual side by side towing comparison and fuel consumption. All that being said, my opinion is still ranger top of the list, bt50 close second, only if they both had the 3.2l, followed by the D-max, then triton. Wait for the sales that are currently going on, and you will see a vastly different price than what you've shown in this video. Can't wait until the middle?? to late year when ford australia releases their version of the killarado, the ranger with a 5.0l from the mustang!! Hope they don't stuff up the drivetrain!! Now get out fishing with Sammy!! lol
